{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637155"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:38:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:38:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17631"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17631"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.91,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10345"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71809"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10345"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57298"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10042"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24244"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71809"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamins are essential micronutrients that must be obtained from dietary sources. Their absorption in the gastrointestinal tract varies based on their chemical properties. Fat-soluble vitamins are absorbed in the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best best describes this absorption?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Occurs primarily in the ileum","Occurs via simple diffusion without carriers","Requires bile salts and micelle formation","Requires intrinsic factor","Uses sodium-dependent co-transport"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, and K) require \u003Cstrong\u003Ebile salts and micelle formation\u003C/strong\u003E for absorption. This is because these vitamins are hydrophobic and need to be packaged into micelles to cross the aqueous environment adjacent to the intestinal epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple diffusion without carriers\u003C/strong\u003E - While fat-soluble vitamins do eventually diffuse across cell membranes, they first require incorporation into micelles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires intrinsic factor\u003C/strong\u003E - This is specific to vitamin B12 absorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium-dependent co-transport\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism is used by some water-soluble vitamins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOccurs primarily in the ileum\u003C/strong\u003E - Fat-soluble vitamin absorption occurs primarily in the jejunum where bile salt concentration is highest\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter absorption, fat-soluble vitamins are packaged into chylomicrons and transported via the lymphatic system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K) require bile salts and micelle formation for intestinal absorption.","Water-soluble vitamins (B and C) are absorbed directly across the intestinal epithelium via specific transport mechanisms.","Vitamin B12 requires intrinsic factor for absorption in the ileum."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019",